EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This white paper addresses the recurring institutional panic in which contemporary observers declare a new machine to be unprecedented, socially destabilizing, economically incomprehensible, and fundamentally incompatible with existing economic theory—despite identical claims being made for at least the last 500 years, and arguably since the controlled use of fire.

The Institute for Retroactive Technological Panic (IRTP) has identified a persistent cognitive phenomenon, herein designated Technological Exceptionalism Recurrence Disorder (TERD), in which each generation insists that its machines are uniquely world-ending while simultaneously using electricity, industrial agriculture, and antibiotics without comment.

This paper formally rejects the claim that economic theory “never accounted for machines that do weeks of human work in seconds,” on the grounds that this is precisely what the steam engine, printing press, mechanized loom, tractor, assembly line, calculator, and computer were specifically invented to do, and in fact did.

The present document therefore proposes a comprehensive framework for remembering things that already happened.

