1. HISTORICAL PRECEDENT FAILURE ANALYSIS (HPFA)

1.1 The Fire Event (Pre-Industrial Automation Phase 0)

Fire allowed one human to perform the work of:
	•	Multiple hours of chewing (cooking)
	•	Several days of walking (land clearing)
	•	Entire winters of shivering (heating)
	•	Manual darkness removal (lighting)

Conclusion: Fire was the original labor-replacing technology and should have triggered mass economic panic under the “machines doing work faster than humans” theory. Instead, civilization occurred.

1.2 The Printing Press Incident (Information Replication Automation)

The printing press allowed one operator to do the work of hundreds of scribes, destroying the medieval manuscript-copying industry at a rate now described as “disruptive.”

Observed consequences:
	•	Mass unemployment among monks (Manuscript Sector)
	•	Explosion of literacy (Unexpected Externality)
	•	Scientific Revolution (Unplanned Feature)
	•	Newspapers (Mixed Results)

Economic theory response: The Industrial Revolution.

1.3 The Steam Engine Overreaction (Mechanical Labor Replacement)

The steam engine replaced:
	•	Human muscle
	•	Animal muscle
	•	Water wheels
	•	Windmills
	•	Entire professions involving pulling ropes very slowly

This resulted in factories, railways, global trade, and economists becoming a permanent feature of society.

At the time, observers stated:

“Machines will take all the jobs.”
— Everyone, 1820

Employment subsequently increased for the next 200 years.

1.4 The Tractor Catastrophe (Agricultural Labor Collapse)

In 1800, ~80–90% of humans worked in agriculture.
Today, in developed economies: ~1–2%.

If the claim “machines that do weeks of human work in minutes break economics” were true, the invention of the tractor should have ended civilization immediately. Instead, it produced cities, universities, and professional podcasts.

